  <content>
    <title>RAG Retrieval Quality Metrics</title>

    <summary>Retrieval metrics measure whether the RAG system fetches the right documents before generation happens. The five core metrics — Precision@K, Recall@K, MRR, NDCG@K, and Hit Rate — are pure-Python computations with zero API cost and should run on every test evaluation.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Retrieval quality is the upstream determinant of generation quality: high faithfulness with low Precision@K means the generator is hallucinating from insufficient context. Measuring retrieval separately isolates root causes — a pipeline can have good end-to-end answer accuracy while silently degrading on recall, which becomes visible only when a new document category is introduced. All five metrics are computable with no LLM calls, making them free to run on every test batch.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Measuring whether the retriever returns relevant documents for a labeled test set (ground-truth relevant doc IDs available).</item>
        <item>Selecting or tuning the retrieval top-K — Precision@K and Recall@K give direct feedback on the K parameter.</item>
        <item>Ranking-quality comparison between two retrieval strategies (e.g., dense vs. hybrid) — use NDCG@K for graded relevance.</item>
        <item>CI quality gate: fail a deployment if Hit Rate drops below 0.90 or Precision@5 drops below 0.70.</item>
        <item>Diagnosing a generation quality problem: if faithfulness is low but Precision@K is high, the problem is the generator, not the retriever.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>When no ground-truth relevant doc IDs exist — Precision@K, Recall@K, MRR, and NDCG@K all require labeled sets; collect labels via human annotation or synthetic test-set generation before applying these metrics.</item>
        <item>Real-time per-query scoring in production — these metrics require a labeled test set comparison, not a single live query; for online monitoring use generation-side signals (faithfulness sampling) instead.</item>
        <item>Replacing generation metrics — high Precision@K says nothing about whether the generator produces faithful, relevant answers; always pair with generation metrics.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="metric-definitions">
      <p>Each metric captures a different aspect of ranking quality. Use the selection table to pick the right metric for the evaluation goal.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Always run all five retrieval metrics together, not just one. Precision@K and Hit Rate together distinguish "few but precise" from "at least one hit" retrieval failures. MRR and NDCG distinguish rank-position quality from recall breadth.</statement>
        <rationale>A retriever can have Hit Rate=1.0 (always returns at least one relevant doc) while Precision@K=0.20 (4 out of 5 docs are irrelevant noise that pollutes the generation context). Single-metric optimization creates blind spots.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <section name="metric-selection-table">
        <p>Metric selection guide:</p>
        <list>
          <item>Precision@K — care about accuracy in top-K; range 0-1; higher means fewer irrelevant docs; divides by K not by number retrieved</item>
          <item>Recall@K — need to find all relevant docs; range 0-1; higher means fewer missed docs</item>
          <item>MRR — first relevant result position matters; range 0-1; penalizes harshly when first relevant doc is ranked 3rd or lower</item>
          <item>NDCG@K — graded relevance (not binary); range 0-1; higher means better ranking quality; requires graded scores</item>
          <item>Hit Rate — only need one relevant doc; binary 0 or 1; insensitive to how many relevant docs were retrieved</item>
        </list>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="implementations">
      <p>Complete standalone retrieval metric suite — no external dependencies beyond numpy for NDCG:</p>

      <example type="good" title="Complete retrieval metrics suite">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from typing import List, Set, Dict
import numpy as np


def precision_at_k(retrieved: List[str], relevant: Set[str], k: int) -> float:
    """
    Precision@K: How many retrieved docs are relevant?

    Args:
        retrieved: List of retrieved document IDs (ordered by rank)
        relevant: Set of relevant document IDs
        k: Number of top results to consider

    NOTE: divides by k, not by len(retrieved). Pass the correct k
    matching the retrieval top-K, not the actual result count.
    """
    retrieved_at_k = set(retrieved[:k])
    relevant_retrieved = retrieved_at_k.intersection(relevant)
    return len(relevant_retrieved) / k


def recall_at_k(retrieved: List[str], relevant: Set[str], k: int) -> float:
    """
    Recall@K: How many relevant docs were retrieved?
    """
    retrieved_at_k = set(retrieved[:k])
    relevant_retrieved = retrieved_at_k.intersection(relevant)
    return len(relevant_retrieved) / len(relevant) if relevant else 0


def mean_reciprocal_rank(retrieved: List[str], relevant: Set[str]) -> float:
    """
    MRR: How highly is the first relevant doc ranked?
    Returns 0.0 when no relevant doc is retrieved — distinguish this from
    MRR=0.0 due to ranking failures when computing macro-average over a test set.
    """
    for i, doc_id in enumerate(retrieved):
        if doc_id in relevant:
            return 1.0 / (i + 1)
    return 0.0


def ndcg_at_k(retrieved: List[str], relevance_scores: Dict[str, float], k: int) -> float:
    """
    NDCG@K: Normalized Discounted Cumulative Gain.
    Considers graded relevance (not just binary).

    If only binary labels exist, set relevance_scores = {doc_id: 1.0 for doc_id in relevant}
    and NDCG degrades to AP (average precision).
    """
    def dcg(scores: List[float]) -> float:
        return sum(
            (2**score - 1) / np.log2(i + 2)
            for i, score in enumerate(scores)
        )

    actual_scores = [relevance_scores.get(doc_id, 0) for doc_id in retrieved[:k]]
    actual_dcg = dcg(actual_scores)

    ideal_scores = sorted(relevance_scores.values(), reverse=True)[:k]
    ideal_dcg = dcg(ideal_scores)

    return actual_dcg / ideal_dcg if ideal_dcg > 0 else 0


def hit_rate(retrieved: List[str], relevant: Set[str]) -> float:
    """
    Hit Rate: Was at least one relevant doc retrieved?
    Binary metric — insensitive to how many relevant docs were retrieved.
    """
    return 1.0 if any(doc_id in relevant for doc_id in retrieved) else 0.0


def compute_retrieval_metrics(
    retrieved: List[str],
    relevant: Set[str],
    k: int = 5,
    relevance_scores: Dict[str, float] = None
) -> dict:
    """Compute all retrieval metrics in one call."""
    result = {
        f"precision@{k}": precision_at_k(retrieved, relevant, k),
        f"recall@{k}": recall_at_k(retrieved, relevant, k),
        "mrr": mean_reciprocal_rank(retrieved, relevant),
        "hit_rate": hit_rate(retrieved, relevant),
    }
    if relevance_scores:
        result[f"ndcg@{k}"] = ndcg_at_k(retrieved, relevance_scores, k)
    return result
]]></code>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Passing k different from the actual retrieval top-K when calling precision_at_k.</description>
        <reason>precision_at_k divides by k, not by number of retrieved docs. If you retrieve top-10 but pass k=5, you measure a different cut than what the retriever actually returned, producing misleading results.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Computing macro-average MRR without distinguishing MRR=0.0 (no relevant doc retrieved) from low-but-positive MRR.</description>
        <reason>mean_reciprocal_rank returns 0.0 when no relevant doc appears in the result list. Averaging this with true MRR scores conflates two different failure modes: missing relevance entirely vs. poor rank position.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Using NDCG@K with binary labels directly from a relevant set without converting to graded scores.</description>
        <reason>NDCG@K requires graded relevance scores (float dict). With binary labels, construct relevance_scores = {doc_id: 1.0 for doc_id in relevant} — this converts NDCG to equivalent of average precision and is explicit about the binary assumption.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="per-use-case">
      <p>Recommended metric combinations by retrieval use case:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Question Answering: Faithfulness (generation) + Precision@3 + MRR — small K because Q&amp;A benefits from precision over breadth</item>
        <item>Document Search: NDCG@10 + Recall@20 + MRR — large K to measure breadth; graded relevance matters</item>
        <item>Chatbot: Context Relevance (generation) + Hit Rate — at least one hit ensures context exists; relevance of that context is the generation-side check</item>
        <item>Summarization: Recall@K dominates — missing a relevant document is worse than including an irrelevant one</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <checklist>
      <check>Ground-truth relevant doc IDs collected for the test set before running any retrieval metric.</check>
      <check>k parameter in precision_at_k and recall_at_k matches the actual top-K used in retrieval.</check>
      <check>All five metrics computed together — no single-metric evaluation.</check>
      <check>NDCG@K uses graded scores or explicit binary-to-float conversion.</check>
      <check>Macro-average MRR computation distinguishes 0.0-miss from 0.0-not-found.</check>
      <check>Retrieval metrics paired with at least one generation metric (faithfulness or context relevance).</check>
    </checklist>

